description: {"blocks":[{"key":"fls1p","text":"The spectrophotometer has been used for decades to measure the density of bacterial populations as the turbidity expressed as optical density – OD. However, the OD alone is an unreliable metric and is only proportionately accurate to cell titers to about an OD of 0.1. The relationship between OD and cell titer depends on the configuration of the spectrophotometer, the length of the light path through the culture, the size of the bacterial cells, and the cell culture density. We demonstrate the importance of plate reader calibration to identify the exact relationship between OD and cells/mL. We use four bacterial genera and two sizes of micro-titer plates (96-well and 384-well) to show that the cell/ml per unit OD depends heavily on the bacterial cell size and plate size. We applied our calibration curve to real growth curve data and conclude the cells/mL – rather than OD – is a metric that can be used to directly compare results across experiments, labs, instruments, and species.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

To achieve that, a mid-log phase culture is required - one in which the culture has not begun to","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"emkro","text":"enter stationary phase.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3bt8u","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"9irkk","text":"There are two easy ways to prepare overnight cultures that are highly reproducible and contain almost","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"brkvv","text":"exclusively viable cells. Both methods involve limiting cell growth before stationary phase has begun.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"a62o","text":"Method 1: Using rich broth media to obtain oxygen-limited cultures","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"b22oa","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ee1o6","text":"Inoculate a colony into 10 ml of your favorite broth medium in a 15 ml plug-seal centrifuge tube, then","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1svra","text":"tighten down the plug-seal cap and allow the culture to stand overnight at the preferred growth","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"6sg7e","text":"temperature without shaking or other method of aeration.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"5qkjm","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ffs36","text":"The details are important. We do not want the culture to be aerated because we want to maintain the","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1hg7s","text":"culture at exponential or early stationary phase. Using the 10 ml of medium in a 15 ml tube allows only","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"a6h6","text":"5 ml of oxygen-containing head space. The plug-seal cap ensures that no additional oxygen is available","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"9dv93","text":"to the growing culture.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5ff3m","text":"A mineral salts medium, such as M9 medium, containing a limiting concentration of a carbon source","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"dlvcq","text":"such as glucose (0.02% w/v) works well for many organisms. Inoculate a suitable volume of carbonlimited","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"cf6tf","text":"medium with a single colony and shake well overnight at the optimum growth temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"2onad","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3don7","text":"A couple of days before doing the calibration, grow either an oxygen limited or nutrient limited culture.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1shss","text":"Measure the OD of that culture in 6 wells of a microtiter plate and the OD of the uninoculated medium","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"bt794","text":"in another 6 wells (the blanks). Subtract the mean OD of the blank wells from the mean OD of the wells","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"4sm5e","text":"containing the culture. That OD is the corrected OD of the nutrient or oxygen limited culture. Use","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"153nd","text":"either a 96-well plate or a 384-well plate containing the volume you typically use in that plate. For this","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"8p2e3","text":"purpose, it doesn't matter which size plate you use.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"2lmga","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"8mthe","text":"The OD units are OD times volume in ml. For example, a 10 ml culture with a corrected OD of 0.3","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"t6td","text":"contains 3 OD units. The purpose of using OD units is to let you determine the volume of limited culture","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"56ifh","text":"you will need for the real experiment.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"26pq0","text":"Calibration","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"f7f6e","text":"Grow a sufficient volume of limited culture to provide at least 10 OD units. For oxygen limited cultures","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1d5j3","text":"this may require several 10 ml cultures. If so, combine the cultures. {"blocks":[{"key":"7lo93","text":"Spin down the culture(s), pour off the supernatant, and resuspend the pellet in 4.0 ml (or more) of M9","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"6089q","text":"buffer with no nutrients.
